# Dataclass Conventions

## Every Dataclass Must Have an Iteration Method

All dataclasses must include an `__iter__` method that yields `(field_name, value)` tuples:

```python
from dataclasses import dataclass, fields

@dataclass
class MetricResult:
    accuracy: float
    precision: float
    recall: float
    f1_score: float

    def __iter__(self):
        for f in fields(self):
            yield f.name, getattr(self, f.name)
```

## Use Iteration Instead of Repetitive Per-Field Code

```python
# BAD — repeating the same operation per field
print(f"accuracy: {result.accuracy}")
print(f"precision: {result.precision}")
print(f"recall: {result.recall}")
print(f"f1_score: {result.f1_score}")

# GOOD — iterate using the built-in method
for name, value in result:
    print(f"{name}: {value}")
```

## Direct Field Access Is Fine

Accessing specific fields directly (e.g. `result.accuracy`) is perfectly fine when only a few fields are needed. The iteration method targets **repetitive per-field code**, not every field access.

## Key Principle

If you find yourself writing the same pattern for each field of a dataclass, **use the `__iter__` method and loop**.
